WEBVTT

00:08.041 --> 00:10.957
(spy music instrumental playing)

00:11.041 --> 00:13.874
(music distorting)

00:16.874 --> 00:18.916
Are of, are of augment?

00:18.999 --> 00:22.624
The are, the are,
truth far stoop from
and, uh, you know.

00:22.707 --> 00:25.457
If of-- If off to of then to.

00:25.540 --> 00:27.165
Mm. Harold and Maude.

00:27.248 --> 00:29.707
(mutters)

00:34.082 --> 00:36.707
(cheery, distorted
music playing)

00:37.540 --> 00:38.665
(sniffs)

00:42.248 --> 00:43.957
♪ ♪

00:50.248 --> 00:51.749
(music stops)

00:55.248 --> 00:57.832
I-- I just ate spoons.

00:57.916 --> 00:59.665
Instead of cereal, I...

00:59.749 --> 01:01.999
I ate... I ate spoons.

01:02.082 --> 01:04.540
I just pooped way wrong.

01:04.624 --> 01:08.499
Mike, I just pooped
way different, okay, dude?

01:08.582 --> 01:10.457
Just insanely different!

01:10.540 --> 01:13.624
We have to get out
of this bunker!

01:13.707 --> 01:16.999
I'm losin' my fucking mind
in this bunker!

01:17.082 --> 01:19.540
(screaming, crying)

01:19.624 --> 01:21.874
-Oh, look! (babbling)
-Huh?

01:24.290 --> 01:26.082
(speaking gibberish)

01:26.165 --> 01:28.499
That's our Willy Wonka!

01:28.582 --> 01:30.041
(whispering):
We get the labcoats.

01:30.123 --> 01:32.373
They give us for gasoline.

01:32.457 --> 01:34.415
We split it Shia-LaBeouf!

01:34.499 --> 01:35.874
Mike: But it's all scrambled!

01:35.957 --> 01:37.707
(grunting disagreement)

01:37.791 --> 01:40.248
-One time, me go wee-wee...
-Mike: Yeah. Uh-huh.

01:40.332 --> 01:43.916
(speaking gibberish)

01:43.999 --> 01:46.041
Ear like, uh, scrambled?

01:46.123 --> 01:47.499
Oh, no, no, no!

01:47.582 --> 01:49.665
Give me seven doo-doos
and I can pee-pee!

01:49.749 --> 01:53.207
Both: I can't wait for money!

01:53.290 --> 01:55.957
(laughing maniacally)

01:57.916 --> 02:01.415
-(thunder rumbling)
-(bagpipes playing discordantly)

02:01.499 --> 02:03.207
(laughter echoing)

02:03.290 --> 02:04.248
(static crackles)

02:04.332 --> 02:06.290
(rock music playing)

02:06.373 --> 02:08.499
(crowd clamoring)

02:10.041 --> 02:13.248
We're here live
in what's been dubbed
the "trial of the century."

02:13.332 --> 02:14.707
It is a complete
shitshow out here.

02:14.791 --> 02:15.957
And I'm Rachel Maddow.

02:16.041 --> 02:18.540
Meh-meh-meh-meh!
(sputtering)

02:18.624 --> 02:20.791
Poo-poo, pee-pee!

02:20.874 --> 02:23.415
Okay, here we go.
Five, four, three,
two...

02:23.499 --> 02:26.665
-(news theme music playing)
-(Soledad continues
vocalizations)

02:27.957 --> 02:29.957
This is Soledad O'Brien,
reporting live.

02:30.041 --> 02:32.957
It's been two months
since animals all over
New York City

02:33.041 --> 02:34.582
were granted the ability

02:34.665 --> 02:37.041
to communicate across
species lines,

02:37.123 --> 02:38.624
all thanks to
the introduction

02:38.707 --> 02:40.582
of Grand Communicator
technology,

02:40.665 --> 02:43.248
spearheaded by noted
Grab Bagger Yumi.

02:43.332 --> 02:45.123
Since its dramatic debut,

02:45.207 --> 02:47.665
the animal world has been
abuzz with heated debates

02:47.749 --> 02:50.082
over a host of
interspecial issues.

02:50.165 --> 02:52.290
But it all leads to this:

02:52.373 --> 02:56.082
the most hotly contested
court case in history.

02:56.165 --> 02:59.123
In just under 24 hours,
we will know the verdict

02:59.207 --> 03:02.290
of this controversial case
and report it live, here,

03:02.373 --> 03:05.123
on the most trusted source
for news in the country,

03:05.207 --> 03:07.457
the Facebook live stream
of Salon.com.

03:07.540 --> 03:09.582
Oh! I'm just getting news
that things are beginning.

03:09.665 --> 03:11.415
-Cameraman: And we're off.
-Damn it, I'm good.

03:11.499 --> 03:12.749
Could you guys tell
I'm drinking?

03:12.832 --> 03:13.957
Can you tell?
(burps)

03:14.041 --> 03:15.499
(crowd clamoring)

03:15.582 --> 03:18.624
♪ ♪

03:18.707 --> 03:20.457
(voice breaks): All rise...
(clears throat) Okay.

03:20.540 --> 03:23.999
All rise for the Honorable
Judge Mom from Malcolm
in the Middle.

03:24.082 --> 03:26.832
-Hello, hello, everyone.
Thank you.
-(cheers and applause)

03:26.916 --> 03:30.665
Without further ado,
we will now begin to answer
the question of our time:

03:30.749 --> 03:32.540
Who is better...

03:32.624 --> 03:35.165
Jim Carrey or Adam Sandler?

03:35.248 --> 03:37.540
(electric rock guitar
riff playing)

03:41.082 --> 03:44.041
Before we get this trial going,
a little housekeeping.

03:44.123 --> 03:45.874
Malcolm, clean up your room!

03:45.957 --> 03:48.540
-(laughter)
-Sorry, old habits.

03:48.624 --> 03:49.999
I wanna be clear.

03:50.082 --> 03:52.457
Neither Jim Carrey
nor Adam Sandler themselves

03:52.540 --> 03:54.499
will be present during
these proceedings.

03:54.582 --> 03:58.041
Don't be fooled.
Those are just two proxy rats
with cutout masks.

03:58.123 --> 03:59.540
-Crowd: Ah!
-(applause)

03:59.624 --> 04:01.457
We'll hear arguments
in three stages.

04:01.540 --> 04:05.165
Mr. Matarese, defending
the career of Jim Carrey
will go first.

04:05.248 --> 04:07.332
Thank you, Judge Mom
From Malcolm In The Middle.

04:07.415 --> 04:09.540
And thank you all
for being here today.

04:09.624 --> 04:11.415
(slurping)

04:11.499 --> 04:12.874
Objection,
Your Honor.

04:12.957 --> 04:14.874
He's clearly taking a sip
for dramatic effect.

04:14.957 --> 04:16.582
-No I wasn't.
I was thirsty!
-Judge: Overruled!

04:16.665 --> 04:18.041
Well, drink faster.
Take a quick sip.

04:18.123 --> 04:19.707
-Phil: Okay, fine!
Okay, okay.
-Overruled!

04:19.791 --> 04:21.707
Right at the top
of the trial
there's an issue--

04:21.791 --> 04:23.707
-You're the one
who's making it an issue!
-Oh, my God.

04:23.791 --> 04:25.041
-Enough!
-Phil: Okay.

04:25.123 --> 04:27.707
Pretty number, hmm?
I love the look of it.

04:27.791 --> 04:30.499
Swoops, tough edges--
it's really something else.

04:30.582 --> 04:35.082
Folks, Mr. Carrey here
has plenty of early career
milestones I could list.

04:35.165 --> 04:38.540
But 1994 is the year
when the dam restricting

04:38.624 --> 04:41.916
Mr. Carrey's talents
to the masses finally gave way!

04:41.999 --> 04:44.041
(gasps, cheers)

04:44.123 --> 04:47.248
-Male: All right!
Ace Ventura, I love it!
-It was a cultural phenomenon.

04:47.332 --> 04:50.540
Halloween costumes, toys,
lunch boxes, the hairstyle!

04:50.624 --> 04:53.916
I mean, when entertainment
was in a mid-'90s dust bowl,

04:53.999 --> 04:55.749
one man had the guts to say,

04:55.832 --> 04:58.041
"All righty, then.
Let's have some fun."

04:58.123 --> 05:01.707
-(cheers, applause)
-The goddamn Mask.

05:01.791 --> 05:03.082
Oh, yeah, that's
one of my favorites.

05:03.165 --> 05:04.957
It was hyperbolic.
It was slapstick.

05:05.041 --> 05:09.415
He had the ability to work
within the constraints
of mid-'90s CGI.

05:09.499 --> 05:14.082
I mean, America saw
the many shades of Jim Carrey,
and not just one shade.

05:14.165 --> 05:16.082
Come on.

05:16.165 --> 05:19.415
In one year, this man portrayed
an animals-rights activist,
detective

05:19.499 --> 05:22.248
and a Jekyll and Hyde-ian
man with a mask?

05:22.332 --> 05:24.290
"Somebody stop me"?

05:24.373 --> 05:26.832
No. Jim, keep going.

05:27.791 --> 05:29.624
-Male: Dumb and Dumber!
-Judge: Wow. Really?

05:29.707 --> 05:31.916
Those three in the same year?

05:31.999 --> 05:33.290
Okay, no, that's insane.

05:33.373 --> 05:35.957
It was. Look it up!
IMDb right now.

05:36.041 --> 05:37.332
-Look it up!
-Holy shit, he's right.

05:37.415 --> 05:38.791
Who wants hats, huh?

05:38.874 --> 05:40.582
1994 hat!

05:40.665 --> 05:41.791
There you go!

05:41.874 --> 05:43.248
This is great, thank you.

05:43.332 --> 05:45.957
Phil: In one year,
this man changed the world.

05:46.041 --> 05:49.332
America had itself
a new bona fide leading man

05:49.415 --> 05:52.290
who just so happened to be
the comedic genius of our time.

05:52.373 --> 05:53.624
Thank you, that's my time.

05:53.707 --> 05:55.582
-Thank you. Thank you.
-(cheers, applause)

05:55.665 --> 05:57.624
-That means a lot.
-Dude, that was really good.

05:57.707 --> 05:59.332
I practiced
saying stuff before.

05:59.415 --> 06:01.290
-You memorized
that whole thing?
-I didn't memorize it,

06:01.373 --> 06:02.499
but I had
the beats in my head.

06:02.582 --> 06:03.749
-Oh, like Curb?
-Yeah.

06:03.832 --> 06:05.957
Defending the career
of Adam Sandler,

06:06.041 --> 06:07.665
Mr. Michael Luciano.

06:07.749 --> 06:09.624
(sighs)

06:09.707 --> 06:13.457
Well, I hate to say it,
but congratulations,
Mr. Matarese. You win.

06:13.540 --> 06:14.624
(crowd gasps)

06:14.707 --> 06:16.874
You win 1994.

06:16.957 --> 06:19.957
Jim Carrey for sheezy
wins 1994.

06:20.041 --> 06:23.165
But, jury, I implore you
to think of the whole career.

06:23.248 --> 06:25.624
That's what this is all about.
Not a flash in the pan,

06:25.707 --> 06:28.165
-but rather a
three-decade-long simmer.
-(sizzling)

06:28.248 --> 06:30.165
Mmm. I'm hungry,
how about you?

06:30.248 --> 06:31.957
-(Mike laughing)
-(crowd laughing)

06:32.041 --> 06:35.540
Adam Richard Sandler
was born in Brooklyn,
New York City,

06:35.624 --> 06:38.165
a hometown kid with a knack
for cracking up the neighborhood

06:38.248 --> 06:40.165
and harboring big
dreams to boot.

06:40.248 --> 06:42.665
Pairing laughs with
an incredible work ethic,

06:42.749 --> 06:46.499
pretty soon early stand-up gigs
led to some impressive TV roles.

06:46.582 --> 06:49.207
Mike (in child's voice):
Little Adam's gonna be
on the TV?

06:49.290 --> 06:52.624
Hey, mister, is
he gonna be a star?

06:52.707 --> 06:55.165
(in normal voice):
That's right,
little sick kid.

06:55.248 --> 06:57.165
-Adam is gonna be a star.
-Crowd: Aww!

06:57.248 --> 07:00.874
-My God, that is
just heartbreaking.
-Phil: It's a fucking balloon.

07:00.957 --> 07:03.874
With his doo-diddly sounds
and ho-hum jingle-jangles,

07:03.957 --> 07:07.373
Adam quickly became in demand
as a young '90s silly boy,

07:07.457 --> 07:09.373
popping up in major
studio gems like

07:09.457 --> 07:11.373
Airheads and Coneheads.

07:11.457 --> 07:13.707
Sounds like--
Sounds like he was
a real bonehead!

07:13.791 --> 07:14.874
(male coughs)

07:14.957 --> 07:16.665
Bailiff:
Aah, snap.
Overruled.

07:16.749 --> 07:18.916
-Forget it. Sorry, I'm sorry.
-Bailiff: That is embarrassing.

07:18.999 --> 07:21.207
Mike:
But these smaller roles
were all leading

07:21.290 --> 07:24.373
to Sandler's holy trifecta
of blooming adulthood.

07:24.457 --> 07:27.207
Horses and horny teens,
I present to you,

07:27.290 --> 07:29.749
Billy Madison,
Happy Gilmore, Big Daddy.

07:29.832 --> 07:32.832
Dog:
It really was three phases
of the man's life.

07:32.916 --> 07:34.916
We grew
as Sandler grew.

07:34.999 --> 07:37.916
Throughout the '90s,
one man epitomized
the generation linking

07:37.999 --> 07:39.791
the hard outer-shell baby boomer

07:39.874 --> 07:42.123
with silly,
prank phone calling
Gen-Xers.

07:42.207 --> 07:47.248
Maybe my client's career
doesn't come in a neat,
little 1994 package.

07:47.332 --> 07:49.582
Maybe Adam Sandler's
just a little messier.

07:49.665 --> 07:51.916
Maybe he shows up
to movie premieres
in gym shorts,

07:51.999 --> 07:53.916
embodying the American dream,

07:53.999 --> 07:56.624
making it
while making it
look fucking easy.

07:56.707 --> 07:58.123
-Crowd: Ah!
-(cheering)

07:58.207 --> 08:00.957
-(clears throat)
Take the hat off!
-Huh? Oh, my God.

08:01.041 --> 08:02.457
-It's shameful.
-Oh, no.

08:02.540 --> 08:03.791
-Mike: Yes, dude!
-Phil: Fuck.

08:03.874 --> 08:06.373
(jabbering mockingly)

08:06.457 --> 08:08.041
Guys, I'm having so much fun.

08:08.123 --> 08:10.082
I wanna see your best
Adam Sandler impressions

08:10.165 --> 08:12.582
-out in the hallway, okay?
Thanks so much.
-Crowd (chanting): Adam! Adam!

08:12.665 --> 08:14.874
I'm gonna take a recess
before the second round.

08:14.957 --> 08:17.207
-Do what you gotta do,
smoke 'em if you got 'em.
-Adam! Adam! Adam!

08:17.290 --> 08:20.999
♪ I just need your ♪

08:21.082 --> 08:25.248
♪ Good vibrations ♪

08:25.332 --> 08:27.665
♪ I've gotten so ill ♪

08:29.041 --> 08:31.957
Matarese,
you're overplaying your hand.

08:32.041 --> 08:34.457
Marcia Clark, please,
just can't we have

08:34.540 --> 08:37.749
our mentor/men-tea times be
without the mentoring for once

08:37.832 --> 08:39.832
and more about the tea?
What is this, jasmine?

08:39.916 --> 08:42.457
Okay, just trying to introduce
some lawyer wisdom.

08:42.540 --> 08:44.832
I mean, it's not like
I'm Marcia fucking Clark
or anything.

08:44.916 --> 08:46.957
Aah, I'm killing myself
out there, Marcia!

08:47.041 --> 08:49.123
I've never worked
on anything this hard
in my life!

08:49.207 --> 08:50.832
-Phil, it's okay.
-(Phil sighs)

08:50.916 --> 08:53.290
The most important part
about being a lawyer is
just have fun!

08:53.373 --> 08:55.665
-'Cause a scene!
Make a ruckus!
-Fuck yeah.

08:55.749 --> 08:58.123
In a courtroom,
you gotta keep people
on their toes.

08:58.207 --> 09:00.248
-Keep 'em guessing.
-Wait. What do
you mean, Marcia?

09:00.332 --> 09:02.290
Oh, I don't know,
like maybe...

09:02.373 --> 09:03.665
-Snap! Snap!
-(firecrackers popping)

09:03.749 --> 09:05.165
-Dance, Phil! Dance!
-Jesus! Marcia, stop!

09:05.248 --> 09:06.499
Stop, stop.
I get it, I get it.

09:06.582 --> 09:09.041
Never let down your guard
when you're around me!

09:09.123 --> 09:10.665
-Sack tap! Sack tap!
-Phil: Ooh, fuck! (groans)

09:10.749 --> 09:11.999
And let that be
a lesson to you.

09:12.082 --> 09:14.332
-(groans) Thanks, Marcia.
-No problem, Phil.

09:14.415 --> 09:17.665
You know, this reminds me
of an old law anecdote:

09:17.749 --> 09:20.041
"The Cypress and the Frog."

09:20.123 --> 09:22.540
-Phil: I don't know it.
Which one's that?
-That's a good one.

09:22.624 --> 09:24.665
-Phil: You wanna tell me?
-Yeah. I'll see ya next week.

09:24.749 --> 09:25.999
-Marcia?
-(glass thunks)

09:26.082 --> 09:27.832
Marcia Clark? Hmm.

09:27.916 --> 09:30.999
Soledad (voice-over):
America's favorite,
Soledad O'Brien!

09:31.082 --> 09:32.332
(Soledad utters
vocal warm-up)

09:32.415 --> 09:36.041
1994. Mike's
imaginary little sick kid.

09:36.123 --> 09:37.540
Some other shit.

09:37.624 --> 09:39.707
These are just some of
the moments that have marked

09:39.791 --> 09:42.165
the first round of arguments
between old friends

09:42.248 --> 09:44.332
Phil Matarese
and Mike Luciano.

09:44.415 --> 09:47.248
Who will win this right now
is anyone's bet.

09:47.332 --> 09:48.832
Cameraman:
And we're off.

09:48.916 --> 09:50.415
-(scattered cheers, hoots)
-Fucking nailed it again!

09:50.499 --> 09:52.415
And I am so drunk right now.

09:52.499 --> 09:55.373
(electric rock guitar
riff playing)

09:55.457 --> 09:56.999
That's actually me on guitar.

09:57.082 --> 09:58.874
-Okay, okay.
Everybody, we're back.
-(gavel pounds)

09:58.957 --> 10:00.207
Do we have commercials
on this show?

10:00.290 --> 10:02.332
First up is, uh... Phil.

10:02.415 --> 10:05.207
Thank you, Honorable
Judge Mom From Malcolm
In The Middle.

10:05.290 --> 10:08.332
Folks, I like to think of myself
as a pretty good lawyer,

10:08.415 --> 10:11.999
but if we're talking about
father-son bonding, 1990s--

10:12.082 --> 10:14.165
Cable Guy!

10:14.248 --> 10:16.582
-I'm sorry. What?
-Ladies and gentlemen
of the court,

10:16.665 --> 10:19.707
my opponent here is
gonna wax poetic
about late-'90s

10:19.791 --> 10:22.373
divorce dynamics
of Liar Liar.

10:22.457 --> 10:24.999
And I can go on about
socioeconomic inequalities

10:25.123 --> 10:26.749
tackled in Mr. Deeds.

10:26.832 --> 10:28.707
We can spend the whole day
picking roses,

10:28.791 --> 10:30.707
but we keep dancing
around the thorns.

10:30.791 --> 10:31.916
What are you doing?

10:31.999 --> 10:33.248
We said we wouldn't
bring up clunkers.

10:33.332 --> 10:35.373
What's the matter?
Afraid of a little prick?

10:35.457 --> 10:38.749
Juror:
Cable Guy was straight-up scary
I mean, it wasn't funny at all!

10:38.832 --> 10:40.290
Juror 2:
We trusted you, Jim!

10:40.373 --> 10:42.248
-We trusted you!
-Marcia: Phil, Phil.

10:42.332 --> 10:45.582
-Ribbit! Ribbit! Ribbit!
-Oh, God. Is that Marcia Clark?

10:45.665 --> 10:47.749
Aah, this is gonna be
a whole thing, this trial.

10:47.832 --> 10:50.540
-Ribbit!
-(quietly): Marcia, I have
no idea what that means.

10:50.624 --> 10:52.540
(quietly):
"The Cypress and the Frog."

10:52.624 --> 10:55.207
-Remember?
-You never told me
what that meant.

10:55.290 --> 10:56.707
You know what?
I'm just gonna
keep going.

10:56.791 --> 10:57.791
It's fine.
(burps)

10:57.874 --> 10:59.582
Mr. Luciano's right.

10:59.665 --> 11:02.749
The Cable Guy is not a normal
Jim Carrey movie by any stretch.

11:02.832 --> 11:05.248
But taking chances
is what an artist does.

11:05.332 --> 11:07.082
-Hit that motherfuckin' slide.
-(slide clicks)

11:07.165 --> 11:09.290
-Goddamn it. What is up
with these clickers?
-(crowd gasps)

11:09.373 --> 11:12.415
Thank you. I'm gonna do
a real quick experiment, okay?

11:12.499 --> 11:15.791
I want everyone
in the courtroom right now
to close their eyes, please.

11:15.874 --> 11:18.165
(quietly): This is great. Now
I'll steal all their wallets.

11:18.248 --> 11:20.123
-No, Marcia, don't.
-Fuck you. Firecracker.

11:20.207 --> 11:21.624
-Judge: What?
Jesus Christ.
-(gavel pounds)

11:21.707 --> 11:23.499
Marcia Clark!
No firecrackers!

11:23.582 --> 11:26.624
Sorry about that, guys.
Close your eyes and
keep 'em closed.

11:26.707 --> 11:30.123
Just trust me, okay?
Now, by a show of hands,

11:30.207 --> 11:33.457
how many of you left the theater
after viewing The Truman Show

11:33.540 --> 11:34.957
and thought to yourselves,

11:35.041 --> 11:37.165
"What if I'm being Truman-ed
right now?"

11:37.248 --> 11:39.123
(Phil laughs)

11:39.207 --> 11:41.499
Now open your eyes.

11:41.582 --> 11:43.791
-Every one of you with
your hand up right now...
-Male: Wow!

11:43.874 --> 11:45.791
-...just took a risk
and it paid off.
-Male: I did it!

11:45.874 --> 11:47.916
-He's right!
-Just as my client
did with Cable Guy.

11:47.999 --> 11:49.457
-Thank you so much.
-(cheers, applause)

11:49.540 --> 11:51.332
I came out of that
movie with my daughter,

11:51.415 --> 11:52.707
I didn't trust her
for a week.

11:52.791 --> 11:55.499
Come on, that argument
doesn't make any sense!

11:55.582 --> 11:57.457
All right, screw it!
The gloves are coming off.

11:57.540 --> 11:59.290
You wanna talk about
Jim Carrey movies?

11:59.373 --> 12:01.165
What the farts was
The Majestic?

12:01.248 --> 12:03.165
-I'll tell you,
it was anything but!
